    slug: "islam-ki-sachayi-aur-science-k-aitrafaat",
    description: `Islam ki Sachayi aur Science k Aitrafaat is an Urdu-language Islamic book whose title translates to "The Truth of Islam and the Admissions of Science," presenting a systematic examination of how modern scientific discoveries and theories consistently affirm, support, and validate the fundamental teachings and claims of Islam. The book addresses the perceived conflict between religion and science that has characterized much of Western intellectual discourse since the Enlightenment, arguing that in the case of Islam, this conflict is illusory and that the Quran, far from being contradicted by scientific knowledge, actually anticipated and accurately described numerous natural phenomena many centuries before they were discovered by modern science. This thesis makes the book a valuable contribution to the growing body of Islamic literature that engages with modern science from a faith-based perspective.

The book organizes its material around specific scientific disciplines and discoveries, beginning with cosmology and the origin of the universe. The author examines Quranic verses that describe the creation of the heavens and the earth, the expansion of the universe, the Big Bang theory, the cosmic smoke (dukhan) mentioned in the Quran, and the eventual collapse of the universe, showing how these descriptions align remarkably with the findings of modern astrophysics and cosmology. The section on embryology and human development is particularly detailed, examining the Quranic descriptions of the various stages of fetal development — from the nutfah (drop of fluid) to the alaqah (clinging clot) to the mudghah (chewed substance) to the izham (bones) clothed with lahm (flesh) — and demonstrating their correspondence with the stages of human embryological development as understood by modern medical science.

The book also covers scientific topics in the areas of geology, including the Quranic description of mountains as pegs or stakes that stabilize the earth's crust, a concept that aligns with the modern understanding of plate tectonics and the role of mountain roots in stabilizing the earth's surface. The section on hydrology examines the Quranic descriptions of the water cycle, the barrier between fresh and salt water, and the darkness of the deep sea, all of which have been confirmed by modern oceanography. Additional sections address the Quranic references to the structure of the atmosphere, the protective function of the sky, the movement of celestial bodies, the origin of life from water, the sex of the bee, and numerous other scientific phenomena. For each topic, the author provides the relevant Quranic verses, their classical interpretations, and the corresponding scientific findings, allowing readers to draw their own conclusions about the remarkable alignment between the Quran and modern science. The book also addresses the philosophical implications of these correspondences, arguing that the inability of any human being in the seventh century to have known these scientific facts independently constitutes strong evidence for the divine origin of the Quran. The Urdu prose is clear and accessible, making complex scientific concepts understandable for general readers while maintaining intellectual rigor.`,
    metaDescription: "Islam ki Sachayi aur Science k Aitrafaat shows how modern science affirms Quranic teachings on cosmology, embryology, geology, and hydrology in Urdu."
