    slug: "islam-kia-hai",
    description: `Islam Kia Hai is an Urdu-language Islamic book whose title translates to "What is Islam?" and serves as a comprehensive introductory text that explains the fundamental teachings, beliefs, practices, and principles of Islam to readers who want a clear, accurate, and thorough understanding of the Islamic faith. The book is designed to serve as a foundational resource for a diverse audience, including new Muslims who are just beginning to learn about their religion, born Muslims who want to deepen their understanding of the basics, non-Muslims who are curious about what Islam actually teaches, and educators who need a reliable reference text for teaching introductory Islamic studies. The book addresses its subject with a balance of accessibility and depth, providing enough detail to be genuinely informative while avoiding unnecessary complexity that might overwhelm beginners.

The book begins with a clear and systematic exposition of Islamic theology (aqeedah), explaining the six articles of faith that form the foundation of the Muslim belief system: belief in Allah and His exclusive right to worship, belief in the angels as created beings who carry out Allah's commands, belief in the revealed scriptures including the Torah, the Psalms, the Gospel, and the Quran, belief in the prophets and messengers from Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all), belief in the Day of Judgment and the Hereafter, and belief in divine decree (qadar). Each article of faith is explained with reference to the relevant Quranic verses and hadith narrations, and common misconceptions about each belief are addressed with clarity and patience.

The second major section of the book covers the five pillars of Islam — the Shahadah (declaration of faith), Salah (prayer), Zakat (obligatory charity), Sawm (fasting during Ramadhan), and Hajj (pilgrimage to Makkah) — providing detailed yet accessible guidance on the requirements, conditions, and proper method of performing each pillar. The section on prayer is particularly thorough, covering the prerequisites of prayer, the method of performing ablution (wudu), the times of the five daily prayers, the structure and units of each prayer, and the common errors that people make in their prayer. The book also covers essential Islamic teachings on morality and ethics, including the importance of honesty, kindness, justice, patience, gratitude, humility, and the prohibition of major sins such as lying, cheating, backbiting, and oppression. The final sections address common questions about Islam, including its position on violence, the status of women, relations with non-Muslims, and the role of reason in faith. The Urdu prose is simple, clear, and well-organized, making this book an excellent starting point for anyone who wants to understand what Islam is and what it teaches.`,
    metaDescription: "Islam Kia Hai is a comprehensive Urdu guide to Islamic beliefs and practices, covering the six articles of faith, five pillars, and core morality."
