    slug: "islam-main-halal-o-haram",
    description: `Islam Main Halal-o-Haram is an Urdu-language Islamic book whose title translates to "The Permitted and the Prohibited in Islam," providing a comprehensive and authoritative guide to the Islamic rulings on what is lawful (halal) and what is unlawful (haram) in all major areas of human life, including food and drink, earnings and business transactions, dress and appearance, social interactions, entertainment, and personal conduct. The book serves as a practical reference guide for Muslims who want to ensure that their daily activities and choices comply with Islamic law, providing clear rulings backed by evidence from the Quran and the authentic hadith of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) while avoiding the extremes of excessive permissiveness on one hand and rigid over-prohibition on the other.

The book begins with an important foundational discussion of the Islamic principles that govern the concepts of halal and haram, explaining that in Islam the default ruling for all things is permissibility — everything is halal unless there is a specific text from the Quran or Sunnah that declares it prohibited. The author explains the five categories of Islamic legal rulings — obligatory (wajib), recommended (mustahabb), permissible (mubah), disliked (makruh), and prohibited (haram) — and how each category affects the moral responsibility of the believer. The book also discusses the wisdom and philosophy behind the Islamic prohibitions, arguing that Allah's commandments are not arbitrary restrictions but are designed to protect human beings from physical, spiritual, moral, and social harm.

The section on food and drink provides detailed rulings on the permissibility of various types of meat, including the conditions that make animal slaughter halal, the types of animals that are prohibited, and the rulings on seafood, vegetarian food, and processed foods. The section on earnings and livelihood covers the Islamic prohibition of interest (riba), gambling (maisir), bribery, fraud, hoarding, monopolistic practices, and other forms of unjust or exploitative economic activity, while providing guidance on permissible business practices, employment, and investment. The sections on dress and social conduct address the Islamic requirements of modesty, the rulings on men's and women's clothing, the prohibition of extravagance and ostentation, and the etiquette of mixed-gender interactions. The book also covers rulings related to entertainment and recreation, including the Islamic position on music, television, movies, sports, and other leisure activities, providing balanced guidance that acknowledges the human need for relaxation while maintaining the boundaries set by Islamic law. The Urdu prose is practical and well-organized, making this book an essential reference for Muslim households and a valuable resource for Islamic educators and counselors.`,
