    slug: "islam-mein-bunyaadi-haqooq",
    description: `Islam mein Bunyaadi Haqooq is an Urdu-language Islamic book whose title translates to "Fundamental Rights in Islam," presenting a systematic and comprehensive exposition of the rights that Islam grants to individuals and groups within society, based on the authoritative sources of Islamic law — the Quran, the authentic Sunnah of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and the consensus of the Muslim scholars. The book addresses a subject of great contemporary relevance, demonstrating that Islam established a comprehensive framework of human rights and social justice over fourteen centuries ago that remains remarkably progressive and relevant by modern standards. The author systematically documents the rights that Islam guarantees to various members of society, showing how the Islamic legal and ethical system balances rights with responsibilities and protects the dignity, freedom, and well-being of every individual.

The book begins with the rights of Allah over His creation, establishing the theological foundation upon which all other rights are built — namely, that all human rights are derived from the authority of the Creator and that true justice can only be achieved when human beings recognize and fulfill their obligations toward Allah. From this foundation, the book proceeds to discuss the rights of the individual over himself, including the right to life, the right to freedom of religion and conscience, the right to education and knowledge, the right to work and earn a livelihood, the right to own property, and the right to personal dignity and honor. Each right is supported with relevant Quranic verses, hadith narrations, and examples from the practice of the Prophet (peace be upon him) and the righteous caliphs.

The book then addresses the mutual rights and obligations within the family structure, which Islam considers the fundamental unit of society. This section covers the rights of husband over wife and wife over husband, the rights of parents over children and children over parents, the rights of siblings, and the rights of relatives. The section on social rights covers the rights of neighbors, the rights of the poor and needy, the rights of orphans, the rights of travelers, the rights of workers and employees, the rights of employers, the rights of debtors and creditors, and the rights of animals and the natural environment. A significant section is devoted to the rights of non-Muslims living in an Islamic state, documenting the protections that Islam guarantees to people of other faiths, including the right to life, property, religious practice, and legal autonomy in their personal matters. The book also covers the rights of the accused and convicted in the Islamic legal system, demonstrating the safeguards that Islamic law provides to ensure fair trials and humane treatment. The Urdu prose is clear and well-referenced, making this book a valuable resource for students of Islamic law, social workers, human rights advocates, and general Muslim readers who want to understand the comprehensive rights framework that Islam provides.`,
